message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Delayed puberty is defined as the absence of sexual development beyond the age when it is expected to have occurred. Among the given options, the absence of testicular enlargement by age of 14 years confirms delayed puberty, as this should typically occur around age 9-14. The other options may be associated with delayed puberty but are not diagnostic.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The Tanner stages of sexual development provide guidance for diagnosing delayed puberty. Testicular enlargement is a reliable indicator of pubertal development and should occur by age 14 years. Linear growth acceleration should occur by age 13 years, but absence of it alone would not be enough to diagnose delayed puberty. Presence of gynecomastia at age 15 years would suggest early puberty. The adult type of pubic hair distribution should occur by age 17-18 years, so absence of it alone would not be enough to diagnose delayed puberty. Therefore, the absence of testicular enlargement by age 14 years is the most reliable indicator of delayed puberty.
